general_description: ...is a conspicuous ovoid collection of neurons creating an eminence on the surface of the rostromedial pole of the amygdala just at the caudomedial end of the main body of the lateral olfactory tract (Atlas; [Paxinos and Watson; 1982] Figs 17 and 18). It is surrounded by a superficial extension of the anterior amygdala which separates the LOT from the olfactory tubercle rostrally; the anterior cortical nucleus laterocaudally; and the bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract and medial amygdala caudomedially. In Nissl sections; three layers can be recognised in the LOT: a molecular layer (1); a superficial dense cell layer (2); and a deep multiform cell layer (3). Layer 1 contains  few scattered small to medium sized cells. Layer 2 consists of a circumscribed oval cell aggregate composed of tightly packed; deeply staining; medium sized pyramidal neurons. Layer 3 is formed by slightly larger; more loosely arranged multiangular cells which cover the top of layer 2 like a cap. In Golgi preparations; the rounded appearance of this nucleus separates it clearly from neighboring structures. Its neuronal population is made up in its greater part of pyramidal and modified pyramidal cells; but also include stellate cells.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract
general_description: ...is a small column of loosely packed cells closely associated with the accessory olfactory tract (Figs.1B; C; 3C). The nucleus accompanies the accessory olfactory tract from just prior to the entrance of the tract into the molecular layer of the anterior part of the amygdala until the tract assumes a position immediately caudal to the LOT. At this caudal level; the BAOT lies ventral to another small group of larger; more darkly staining neurons; anterior ventral dense celled subdivision of Me (MeAV). The cells in BAOT are slightly larger and more darkly staining than those in the remaining subdivisions of Me or those in ACo. Further; its lack of stratification provides and easy means of delineation from LOT. The BAOT corresponds very closely to the depiction of the bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract (Scalia and Winans; 1975 and to the description by Krettek and Price (1978b).

general_description: ...is a transition region inserted between the amygdala and the rostral basal forebrain structures. It lacks the stratified arrangement seen in other superficial amygdaloid nuclei; and appears as a diffuse mass of lightly stained cells of different sizes and shapes. but with a predominance of medium sized elements with oval or slender triangular cell bodies. Just caudal to the olfactory tubercle; AA reaches the brain surface and persists in this superficial position until LOT appears. Medial to the LOT; the superficial or ventral part of the AA continues caudally until it merges with medial amygdaloid nucleus. Laterocaudally; the rostral pole of the anterior cortical nucleus intervenes between the AA and the brain surface. In the ventral part of the AA; cells of different sieze and shape are found within the molecular layer as the boundary line between sublaminae 1-alpha and !A; a characteristic arrangement the ventral AA shares only with the ACo and BAOT. Rostrodorsally; where the AA borders with fundus striati; the AA stands out by its lesser packing density and larger cells. Caudodorsally and dorsomedially; it becomes continuous with the medial division of the central amygdaloid nucleus and with the sublenticular parts of the substantia innominata; respectively. At this location; it is very difficult to trace a boundary line. Around the LOT; the medium siezed predominantly spindle shaped AA neurons are arranged in a ring-like formation several rows thick; surrounding the LOT; except its ventral superficial side and at th exit point of the commissural stria terminalis.

general_description: Extends anteroposteriorly fomr the laterocaudal aspect of ACo to the posterior limb of the amygdaloid fissure which separates it from APir (Fig. 3; D; E; F). Throughout its length the PLCo abouts the piriform cortex laterally; while medially it is continuous with the ACo at rostral levels; and he PMCo caudally. Dorsally; it blendas in a rostrocaudal succession with the ventral part of the basolateral amygdaloid nucleus; basomedial amygdaloid nucleus; posterior basolateral amygdaloid nucleus (BLP) and anterolateral amygdalohippocampal transition area. Cytoarchitecturally; the PLCo appears as a collection of cells clustered into five cell subgroups: oral medial; oral lateral; caudal medial; small celled; and caudal lateral. The most conspicuous differentiating features are those shown by the oral medial; caudal medial; and small celled subgroups. ...at the level of its posterolateral subdivision is made up in its greater part of small and medium sized pyramidal and modiefied pyramidal cells. Horizontal; fusiform; and polygonal cells also contribute to its neuronal population but to a much lesser degree than the pyramids. The PLCo corresponds to the lateral part of the amygdala superficialis caudalis ventralis of Uchida (1950) that surrounds his "nucleus amygdalae parvocellularis corticalis"; Uchida's "parvocellularis" is represented by the present small celled subdivisions of the PLCo. The rostral of the amygdalopiriform transition area of Yu (1969) is included in this account of PLCo. Except for the difference in terminology; the descriptions by Krettek and Price (1978b) and Haberly and Price (1978) of the "periamygdaloid cortex" coincides in almost every regard with this account of the PLCo. Their nomenclature for this amygdaloid field was not used because Bayer (1980) demonstrated that the PLCo neurogenesis corresponds to a subcortical nucleus in that it had a superficial to deep gradient similar to the PMCo.

brain_part: Central amygdaloid nucleus lateral division central subdivision
general_description: The CeLcn appears in the caudal two thirds of the nucleus as an ellipsoid cell condensation surrounded in a cup-like fashion by CeLC which intervenes between the CeLcn and IMG rostrally; dorsally; laterally and caudolaterally; and between the CeLcn and IMG; and anterior and posterior BM ventrally. Medially; the CeM closes the cup. At its rostral end; CeLcn becomes condensed into a spherical cell mass of reduced dimensions (around 400 micrometers). Neurons in this rostral condensation are not only more tightly packed but also significantly more basophilic than those in the main body of the CeLcn. Because of this configuration and chemoarchitectural characteristics; this cell conglomerate has been considered as a separate entity; for example the central intermediate nucleus of McDonald (1982a).

general_description: ...is a relatively homogeneous mass of palley staining small and medium sized neurons (Atlas [Paxinos; 1982]; Fig. 20). It extends from a level just caudal to the cephalic pole of the anterior basolateral nucleus until nearly the caudal end of the amygdaloid complex; occupying the dorsal aspect of the basolateral nucleus complex and enlarging as it progresses caudally (Figs. 1C; 2; 3C; D; E; 4A). On the basis of cell morphology and topography; the La can be divided into dorsolateral (LaDL); ventromedial (LAVM); and ventrolateral (LaVL) parts. The Golgi morphology of nerurons in the La; like those in the remaining divisions of the basolateral complex can be grouped in two primary types: pyramidal and non-pyramidal. The pyramidal neurons; which are undoubtely the predominant cell type in the whole basolateral nuclear complex; have a configuration closely resembling that of an isocortical pyramidal cell. The above description of the La corresponds closely to that by Krettek and Price (1978b). The present description differs markedly from the accounts by Gurdjian (1928) and Brodal (1947).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: In the subprimate mammals; the amygdalopiriform transition area (APir) is the gray formation situated in the fundus and the lateral lip of the shallow amygdaloid or semiannular (Fig. 3F) fissure and is formed of an anterior and posterior portion. The anterior portion is narrow and is interposed between the temporal (posterior) piriform cortex laterally; and the superficial amygdala (that is; PLCo) medially. The expanded posterior APir is intercalated between the ventromedial (VMEnt) (VMEA; Krettek and Price; 28M'; Haug) and ventrolateral (VLEnt) (VLEA; Krettek and Price; 28L'; Haug) subdivisions of the entorhinal periallocortex and the caudolateral pole of the superficial amygdala (here the PMCo). The APir differentiates itself from the other structures which surround it by the amplitude in its molecular layer (layer 1) and the lack of a defined segregation of its superficial and deep cells. Rostrally; at the level of the anterior APir; both the superficial (2) and deep (3) layer are typically displaced towards the depth of this cortical sector. Cells in the deeper stratum are; however; larger than those in the superficial one. Laterally and caudally; the superficial stratum appears broken up in roughly spherical clusters of cells. The neuronal population of the APir is morphologically and chemically heterogeneous. It contains modified pyramids; spindle shaped cells; and polymorph cells. The APir corresponds approximately to the transition zone of Haug (1976); the most anteroventral sector of VLEA (Krettek and Price; 1977c); the VLEA transition zone and BLP transition zone (Ottersen; 1982); and the transition zone of Kosel et al. (1981).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: On the basis of cytoarchitectural; fibroarchitectural and chemoarchitectural criteria; four major nuclei can be recognized as constituents of the basolateral amygdaloid group: lateral (La); basolateral (BL); ventral basolateral (BLV) and basomedial (BM). This heterogeneous assemblage of neurons occupies 48.8% of the total volume of the rat amygdala (Herzog; 1982).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The principal nuclei of the medial amygdaloid group include those associated with the accessory olfactory system; and with the medial division of the hypothalamus. In addition to those structures normally considered in association with the medial amygdala; we have included part of the sublenticular substantia innominata and the medial division of the BST. Also; on hodologic considerations; we have included the bed nucleus of the commissural division of the stria terminalis (BCST); the intra-amygdaloid bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (BSTIA); and the amygdalohippocampal transition area. Two systems of projections seem to characterize the medial amygdaloid group. The first system consists of reciprocal connections with the accessory olfactory bulb...The second system of projections most typical for the medial amygdaloid group are to the medial preoptic area.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: A closer examination reveals cytoarchitectural differences within which provide basis for its subdivision into anterolateral (deep lying) and posteromedial (superficial) parts. The anterolateral AHi contains cells which resemble slightly those in the posterior BL...Collator note: the abbreviation of this part can be found in FGigure 3.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nuclei of the stria terminalis
general_description: ..generally classified as a member of the caudal group of septal nuclei. The BST forms the floor of the lateral ventricle and is bounded dorsomedially by the ventral aspect of the lateral septal nucleus; and laterally by the internal capsule which separates it from caudate-putamen and globus pallidus (Figs. 3A; 4A; 5A; B; C; 6A to E; 7F). Caudally; it is successively bounded by the stria medullaris and in part by the columns of the fornix. Rostrally; it is bounded by the nucleus accumbens; while ventrally it merges with the preoptic area. Collator note: this term is not captured in a hierarchy; its subparts are components of the different amygdaloid nuclei.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...is a prominent member of the superficial amygdala and occupies its rostromedial aspect (Figs. 1B; C; 3C; D; 4C). It consists almost entirely of small and medium sized lightly stained cells of various shape. It also contains some large cells which are more abundant towards the rostrodorsal aspect of the nucleus. The Me begins just caudal and medial to the LOT; overlying for a short distance the BAOT; and extends caudally until the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle appears. At this level; it lies dorsomedial to the cephalic pole of the AHi and forms the medial aspect of the anterior wall of this portion of the hemispheric ventricle. Along its entire extent the Me lies in direct apposition tot the ventrolateral side of the optic tract. On cytoarchitectural grounds; the Me is subdivided into a principal part or body; a small dense celled anteroventral part (MEAV) and a posterodorsal part (MEPD) at the caudal end of the nucleus (Price; 1981). In Golgi stained material (Fig. 7B); the ME displays mostly small neurons (5 micrometers-`0 micrometers) with a more radiate and extended (isodendritic) configuration. The Me includes both the medial amygdaloid nucleus of Yu (1969) and his "medial area (CO 3)" of the cortical nucleus. The present delineation of the Me subnuclei corresponds quite closely with the ones proposed by Bayer (1980) and Turner and Zimmer (1984).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis oval nucleus
general_description: This is a roughly oval shaped; compact group of uniformly medium-sized round to- oval neurons (Figs. 11;12). It is centered in midrostrocaudal levels of the anterolateral area where it lies dorsally; just medial to the internal capsule.
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture
referenceforfacet: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

general_description: ...constitutes the caudal third of the superficial amygdala lying posterior to the Me and caudomedial to the PLCo (Fig. 3E; F). The posterior limb of the amygdaloid fissure signals superficially its separation from the caudomedial tail of the AHi and from the ventromedial transitional entorhinal cortex (VMEnt). Dorsally; it is capped almost completely by the remainder of the AHi and the hippocampal formation. In cell preparations; the PMCo appears as a homogeneous; relatively well circumscribed ovoid mass of small and medium sized; palely staining cells which is separated from the pial surface by a molecular layer. The existence of an incipient stratification in the PMCo is consistent with the earlier neurogenesis of the superficial cells (E15-E16) as compared with the deeper lying ones (E16-E17) (Bayer; 1980). In Golgi preparations; the PMCo (Fig. 7E); like the other two cortical subnuclei; consists of a majority of modified pyramids whose rather thick; sparsely branched but spiny apical dendrites project to the depth of the nucleus. Mixed with modified pyramids; it is possible to find fusiform and polymorph (stellate) cells generally located in the depth of the nucleus.The PMCo corresponds to the amygdala superficiale caudalis ventralis superficialis of Uchida (1960); the posterior cortical nucleus of Yu (1969); the posterior cortical nucleus of Krettek and Price (1978b); and to the posteromedial cortical nucleus of Turner and Zimmer (1984).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...is a prominent member of the corticomedial nuclear complex located in the caudal ventromedial angle of the amygdaloid body; immediately caudal to the posterior part of Me and lies in direct continuity with the ventral subiculum caudomedially; and with the medial extension of the APir; which spearates it from the ventrolateral subdivision of the entorhinal periallocortex; caudally (Fig. 3D; E; F). The AHi forms a shallow basked-like formation around the dorsal and caudomedial aspect of the PMCo from which; in some places; it is indistinctly separated. On its lateral aspect; AHi merges with the posterior BM rostrally; and successively with the posterior BL and the main body of the APir caudally. Dorsally; it is in successive topographic relationship with th MePD; the floor of the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle; and the region superior (field Ca1) of Ammon's horn. It is separated from the last two by fiber bands joining the stria terminalis. A closer examination reveals cytoarchitectural differences within which provide basis for its subdivision into anterolateral (deep lying) and posteromedial (superficial) parts. In Golgi preparations; the AHi is composed of pyramidal and polygonal cells which resemble structurally those seen in posterior BL. The AHi corresponds approximately to the caudal part of the medial nucleus described by Brodal (1947). the amygdalohippocampal transition area described by Yu (1969); and the posteromedial basal nucleus described by Scalia and Winans (1975).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial; anterior part
general_description: The anterior BSTM is located dorsal to the crossing fibers of the anterior commissure; lying within the course of the dorsal component of the stria terminalis as it traverses the dorsal and rostral aspects of the commissure. It borders the ventral lateral septum rostromedially; and reaches the rostrodorsal border of the BSTV ventrocaudally. Dorsally; the stria terminalis separates the anterior BSTM from the posterior BSTM while ventrally the anterior and posterior BSTM are separated by the commissural component of the stria terminalis. Medially; the cells of the anterior BSTM are medium sized and irregular in shape and dispersed among the fibers of the stria terminalis. More laterally; the cells are smaller and more tightly packed. The anterior BSTM corresponds to a subpart of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (Swanson 1976) and Swanson and Cowan (1979) while the posterior BSTM cuts across their medial and preoptic BST. The anterior and posterior BSTM; as well as the BSTI are included within the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis of McDonald (1983a). The anterior BSTM is included within the "a" division of the BST of Bleier et al. (1979); which also encompasses our dorsal parts of the small celled and medium celled columns of the posterior BSTM.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial; posterior part
general_description: The anterior BSTM is located dorsal to the crossing fibers of the anterior commissure; lying within the course of the dorsal component of the stria terminalis as it traverses the dorsal and rostral aspects of the commissure. It borders the ventral lateral septum rostromedially; and reaches the rostrodorsal border of the BSTV ventrocaudally. Dorsally; the stria terminalis separates the anterior BSTM from the posterior BSTM while ventrally the anterior and posterior BSTM are separated by the commissural component of the stria terminalis. The posterior BSTM is heterogeneous group of cells arranged in columnar fashion following the postcommissural fibers of the stria terminalis. It is the largest and longest of all divisions of the BST; behind the anterior commissure to the hypothalamus where it merges with anterior hypothalamic area. The anterior BSTM corresponds to a subpart of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (Swanson 1976) and Swanson and Cowan (1979) while the posterior BSTM cuts across their medial and preoptic BST. The anterior and posterior BSTM; as well as the BSTI are included within the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis of McDonald (1983a). ... the "a" division of the BST of Bleier et al. (1979) ... encompasses our dorsal parts of the small celled and medium celled columns of the posterior BSTM.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the commissural component of the stria terminalis
general_description: ...appears as cell groups interspersed among the fibers of the commissural component of the stria terminalis. These cell masses are made up of medium to large cells that stain more lightly than those in surrounding areas. The BCST extends from the dorsolateral surface of the anterior commissure becoming interposed between the posterior BSTM and BSTI. These cells maintain a close relationship with the commissural fibers of the stria terminalis; but do not possess any distinctive boundary. They are rather scattered in and around the fibers from which their name is derived.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: Small; desnely packed cells occupy the entire extent of the LADL...The distinction beween the dorsolateral and ventromedial La are also verifiablw in ACHE reacted and Timm's impregnated sections (Figs 3D; E). The LADL gives a moderate AChE staining reaction (Atlas [Paxinos; 1982] Plate 20); but a weak Timm's reaction which contrasts with the very weak ACHE staining reaction (Atlas [Paxinos; 1982] Plate 22) and the very immense Timm's impregnation in the neuropil of the LAVM. ...the dorsolateral La and ventromedial La are equivalent to; respectively; the dorsal and ventral portion of the amygdala propia lateralis of Uchida (1950); the small celled dorsolateral and large celled ventromedial parts of the lateral nucleus of Yu (1969); and to the lateral and medial divisions of this nucleus by Turner and Zimmer (1984; see also Price; 1981).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...the LAVM; the main division; is made of slightly larger; more scattered and palely staining cells (than LaDL). This cytoarchitectural disctinction is further supported by the poorer fiber content in LaVM. The distinction beween the dorsolateral and ventromedial La are also verifiablw in ACHE reacted and Timm's impregnated sections (Figs 3D; E). The LADL gives a moderate AChE staining reaction (Atlas [Paxinos; 1982] Plate 20); but a weak Timm's reaction which contrasts with the very weak ACHE staining reaction (Atlas [Paxinos; 1982] Plate 22) and the very immense Timm's impregnation in the neuropil of the LAVM. ...the dorsolateral La and ventromedial La are equivalent to; respectively; the dorsal and ventral portion of the amygdala propia lateralis of Uchida (1950); the small celled dorsolateral and large celled ventromedial parts of the lateral nucleus of Yu (1969); and to the lateral and medial divisions of this nucleus by Turner and Zimmer (1984; see also Price; 1981).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...is a collection of large; well staining cells in Nissl sections; which spans the entire rostrocaudal extent of the basolateral complex; appearing rostrally earlier than its dorsolateral; ventromedial and ventral companions; the La; BM; and BLV respectively; and extending further caudally than any of them. Anteriorly; the BL is composed of slightly larger and darker staining cells than posteriorly; and for this reason; a subdivision of the nucleus in anterior (BLA) and posterior (BLP) parts has been proposed (Krettek and Price; 1978b). Golgi preparations (Fig. 7C) show that except for differences in size; the large pyramidal neurons in the BL are practically identical in configuration to those described in the La. The preceding description of the BL is very similar to that presented by Krettek and Price (1978b). This; in turn; agrees well with the general description given by McDonald (1982b). The BL corresponds to the large celled part of the basal nucleus of Yu (1968); as well as to AB1 and AB3 subdivisions of the basal nucleus by Turner and Zimmer (1984).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: Due to relatively smalled and lighter staining of its cells; the BLP cannot be easily distinghuished from the LaVM at those levels in which the LaVL does not intervene between these two nuclei. As pointed out by Yu (1969); small groups of intercalated cells interposed intermitently between the LA and posterior BL help to trace their common boundary. Caudal to the BLA; the BLP is striated because of a multitude of small bundles of fibers which course through this subdivision to join the longitudinal association bundle. The presence of these bundles also helps to differentiate at this level the BLP from the La...On the basis of Golgi-Kopsch material; McDonald (1982b) reported a differential distribution of nonpyramidal cell types in which his multipolar cells were most numerous in the BLA and his double tufted cells more numerous in the BLP.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: This irregular mass of large and medium sized; deeply staining cells makes its appearance as a transverse plane just caudal to the LOT and extends caudally until it merges with the rostral unfolding of the amygdalopiriform transition area (Figs 1C; 3C; D; 4B). In neurofibrillary preparations (Fig. 1C); the BLV cells are surrounded by a dense plexus of transversely coursing fibers which becomes denser toward the dorsal and ventral boundaries of the nucleus; butlighter medially. In Golgi material; the BLV displays pyramidal and other cells similar to those in the La and BL. Dendrites of some of these cells project ventrally into the core of the olfactory cortex or PLCo.The BLV has not been recognized as a separate entity in most descriptions of the amygdaloid cortex.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The lateral division of the central amygdaloid nucleus extends along the entire posterior length of Ce forming a relatively homogeneous ovoid shaped of medium sized cells of similar appearance and chromophilia to those of adjacent striatum. In fiber preparations (Figs 1C; 2); the CeL appears practically encapsulated by small bundles of fibers which separate it from its sibling medially; from the striatum rostrally; dorsally and caudally; and the intramedullary gray (IMG) and basolateral nuclear complex laterally and ventrally. The bulk of this division is characteristically fiber poor.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The ventral endopiriform nucleus (EnV) as we describe it here; and as shown in Figs 1C; 3C; D is a loose arrangement of neurons in the deep part of the primary olfactory cortex; partly interspersed between it and the more ventral components of the external capsule ventrally; while dorsally it becomes separated from the external capsule by the compact portion of the endopirirform nucleus (EnD; volume 1; chapter 1). This area is best appreciated in Timm's stained section (Figs 3C; D; 4B) as a very lightly stained area deep to the darkly staining deepeest layers of the olfactory cortex and adjoining the moderately stained EnD and BLV. Although we have used the same nomenclature; this differs from the description of EnV by Krettek and Price (1978b) which includes the BLV.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...is formed by two ovoid cell masses succeeding one another in the rostrocaudal direction (Figs 1C; 3C; D; E; 4B; C). In AChE preparations; the BM shows; in general; a very poor staining reaction which contrasts markedly eith the very strong one in the BL (Fig. 4C). In Golgi preparations (Fig. 7D); the BM shows very similar neuronal types to those in the La and BL. However; the pyramidal cells in the BM are the smallest in the basolateral complex (in soma size; thickness of dendrites and number of dendritic branch points). Modified pyramids are more frequently found in BM than in the other members of the complex. The BM of the present account corresponds to: (i) the amygdala propria medialis of Uchida (1950 and his amaygdala superficialis oralis intermedia; (ii) the smaller celled part of the accessory basal nucleus of Yu (1969) and his small celled part of the basal nucleus; (iii) in part to the basomedial amugdaloid nucleus of Krettek and Prices (1978b); (iv) Turner and Zimmer's (1984) basal nucleus of the amygdala; posteromedial part and their basal accessory nucleus of the amygdala; and (v) the posterior and anterior parts of Bayer's (1980) basomedial nucleus.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The rostral collection of cells or anterior subdivision [...] is bordered throughout its anteroposterior extent by the BLV laterally; central amygdala and main intercalated cell mass dorsally; and ACo and PLCo ventrally. The anterior BM is made up predominantly of small and medium sized; lightly staining neurons which become rather densely packed dorsally and caudally; rostrally and ventrally they mingle diffusely with those belonging to ACo and the anterior amygdaloid area.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The anterior AStr contains more loosely packed cells and fiber plexus than its posterior counterpart. Acetylcholinesterase material reveals also a stronger activity in the anterior AStr though lower than in the rest of the striatum...Collator note: the authors do not provide an abbreviation for this division of the AStr. The abbreviation was adopted by the collator.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The posterior subdivision [of BM] is flatter and narrower than the anterior BM; it is surrounded dorsally; laterally and caudally by the BLP and BLA; while medially and ventrally it is bordered by the AHi and PLCo. In comparison with the anterior BM; the posterior BM is made up of slightly larger and more darkly staining neurons. They show a more scattered arrangement; and as a result it is difficult at times to delineate the posterior BM from its dorsolateral escort the BL; the overlying PLCo; and the more laterally and deeply lying cells of AHi.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: What appears to be a ventral prolongation of the AStr together with the numerous small clusters of intercalated cells surrounded by the AStr constitute the amygdaloid intramedullary griseum (IMG) (Figs 1C; 2). The IMG is a thin cell and fiber plate that fills the corridor extending between the CelL and La; and BL nuclei. Fibers belonging to the longitudimil association bundle run through the IMG and also highlight its medial boundary. In addition to the intercalated cell masses; the IMG contains medium sized; palely staining fusiform or oval shaped neurons very loosely arranged in the spaces left free by the clusters of intercalated cells.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: ...is an ovoid mass of cells in the dorsal central part of the anygdaloid complex bordered dorsolaterally by the striatum and dorsomedially by the caudal extension of the basal nucleus of Meynert which separates it from globus pallidus. Laterally and ventrallym the Ce is flanked by the La and BL rostrally; and by the transverse limb of the main intercalated cell mass ventrally. Further caudally; the intraamygdaloid part of the BST becomes interposed between the Ce and the caudal limb of Im; while medially a cell poor zone separates the Ce from Me. At its rostral end; the Ce lacks clear boundaries as it blends intimately with the AA and sublenticular substantia innominata. Caudally; a cell poor lamina and the small islands of intercalated cells practically separate the Ce from the anterior wall of the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle. The existence of a very rich fiber plexus in the CeM and the almost complete absence of it in the CeL constitute a major differentiating landmark between these two divivisions of the Ce (Fig. 2). As seen in Golgi preparations; CeM are typically isodendritic (Ramon-Moliner and Nauta 1966). Their usually fusiform or triangular cell boides isssue two to four spine sparse daughter dendrites. The axons of these cells; born either from the cell body or a primary dendrite; send off several fine collaterals along their intranuclear course before leaving CeM.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: The CeM characteristically envelops the upper segments of the intra-amygdaloid course of the commissural stria terminalis; and; in cell preparations; it can be differentiated from its lateral counterpart by its larger; more heterogeneous and darkly staining neurons. The borders of CeM with other neighboring grisea are; on the contrary; not well defined. It merges gradually with the AA and SLSI rostrally; with the caudal extension of the basal nucleus of Meynert dorsomedially; and the intra-amygdaloid BST caudally.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis posterior division
general_description: The posterior division lies caudal to the main bundles ofthe dorsal and commissural bundles of the stria terminalis.As the caudal limits of the anterodorsal area are approached;most of the dorsal region is dominated by thesefibers (Fig. 4); and it is caudal to this that the cellular elementsof the posterior division appear.
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

general_description: The amygdalostriatal transition zone (AStr) encompasses that part of the striatum which is wedged between the Ce and the basolateral nuclear group (Figs 1C; 2; 3C; D). Its cell population consists mostly of smaller; more loosely packed and lightly stained cells than those in the remaining striatum; from which the AStr is discontinuously separated by small; transversely oriented bundles of fibers running at the border between the two structures. Ventromedially; it is also difficult to trace a boundary with the CeL except for the presence of small bundles of fibers interrupting the continuity between the two grisea. Ventro­laterally; the border of the AStr with the basolateral complex is easier to trace because of the interposition of the fiber encapsulated IMG. Two main divisions can be recognized in AStr; anterior and posterior.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis juxtacapsular nucleus
general_description: This is a narrow vertical strip of cells adjacent to the internal capsule; ventral to midrostrocaudal levels of the oval nucleus. In fact; the dorsal part of the juxtacapsular nucleus is wedged between the internal capsule and the oval nucleus. The cellsin this nucleus are much like those in the oval nucleus; although they tend to be somewhat smaller (Figs. 11; 12). This cell group was first named by McDonald ('83).
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

general_description: The intercalated nuclei (I; Atlas Figs 17 to 21) are oval and elongated plate-like clusters of small to medium sized (15 micrometers-20 micrometers); tightly packed neurons located within the spaces existing: (i) between certain amygdaloid nuclei; (ii) between some amygdaloid nuclei and the striatum; and (iii) along the longitudinal association bundle; the intra-amygdaloid portion of the stria terminalis; and between the La or BL and the external capsule; that is; the paracapsular groups (Figs 1A; B; C; 3B; C; 4C).
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Main intercalated nucleus of the amygdala
general_description: Serial horizontal sections reveal that the most conspicuous representatives of I cells constitute in reality a continuous irregular "Z" shaped cell column; the main intercalated mass or nucleus (Im). The Im lies rostral and ventral to the cephalic poles of the anterior BL (Atlas Figs 18; 19) and the transverse (Atlas Fig. 19) and medial sagittal (Atlas Fig. 21) bars of this cluster are interposed successively between: (i) the Ce and anterior BM; (ii) the interior BL/anterior BM and Me; and (iii) the anterior BM/posterior BM and AHi. The cells in Im are stellated in appearance and their dendrites are spine rich. The axons of these cells also emit local collaterals while a single branch runs dorsally towards either the Ce or the longitudinal association bundle.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis anterodosal area central core
general_description: The central region of this area is characterized by a higher density of larger; triangular and multipolar cells interspersed among the smaller cells (Fig. 9). We have called this the central core of the anterodorsal area rather than a nucleus because it is difficult to draw a clear boundaryaround it.
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis lateral subdivision
general_description: The lateral division of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (BSTL) is in the general form of an irregular truncated pyramid with its base apposed to the medial side of the internal capsule; which forms its medial boundary (Figs 4A; SA; B; C; 6A; B; C; 7F). Rostrally; it adjoins the posterior aspect of the nucleus accumbens ventrally and the caudate-putamen dorsally. The medial boundary of the BSTL is marked by the compact fibers of the stria terminalis. It rests atop the anterior commissure and extends slightly rostral along its anterior limb. Caudally; it dips ventrally to surround the posterior face of tpe posterior limb of the anterior commissure. Moving from rostrodorsal to caudoventral; the BSTL tapers somewhat until it fuses with the rostromedial end of the SLSI.In general; cells in the BSTL are somewhat larger and more loosely packed than those in the BSTM. Based on cytoarchitecture and histochemical criteria; the BSTL can be divided into four subdivisions: juxtacapsular; dorsal; ventral and posterior.

general_description: The juxtacapsular BSTL is a small lens shaped cell aggregate made up of small ovoid cells that fill a shallow concavity made by the medial surface of the internal capsule at the same plane as the crossing fibers of the anteriort'commissure. Its medial edge borders the dorsal and posterior BSTL; but is distinguishable from these latter areas by its smaller and more densely packed cells.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis supracapsular part
general_description: The neurons of the supracapsular part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (BSTS) in many mammals form a continuous column following the dorsal course of the stria terminalis. In the rat; intermittent cell pockets may be observed along the course of this tract. These neurons are fusiform and oriented parallel to the axons of stria terminalis. They become scarser in the retrocapsular portion of the amygdala; but increase in number at the entrance of the stria terminalis to the amygdala. While these neurons are difficult to locate in normal histochemical stains; many exhibit a granular argyrophilia similar to neurons in the dorsal part of the BSTL; and the CeL. Alternatively; they may be observed after retrograde labeling from the SLSI or brain stem [...].

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis transverse nucleus
general_description: This relatively small nucleus lies at mid-dorsoventral levels in the lateral part of the posterior division. It is essentially a thin sheet of  cells embedded within the interfascicular nucleus and lateral parts of the principal nucleus. The neurons in the transverse nucleus can be distinguished rather easily from those in the surrounding nuclei on two grounds. First; they are considerably more heterogeneous in shape and size; and second; their perikarya tend to assume a characteristic transverse orientation.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis anterodorsal area
general_description: This region lies dorsal to the anterior commissure and is contiguous with the anteroventral area rostra1 and caudal to the commissure. Most of the cells in the anterodorsal area are small and round to oval in shape; although a few cells with different characteristics are intermingled among this major type (Figs. 9; 10). The density of cells in this area is generally quite high; although at more caudal and dorsal levels it decreases somewhat because of the ventrally coursing fibers of the stria terminalis (Fig. 3)

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminals lateral subdivision
general_description: The lateral subdivision of BST; located at the level of the anterior commissure (Fig. 1) consists of a fairly homogeneous population of spiny neurons (Fig. 2; cell B). These ceils have ovoid perikarya that average 17x 14 micrometers in diameter; and 4-5 primary dendrites that radiate in all dircctionr Dendrites branch several times and extend 150-200 micrometers from the cell body. Perikarya and primary dendrites exhibit few spines but secondary and more distal dendrites have a dense covering of spines (Fig. 2; cell B). Most spines consist of a short stalk capped by a small terminal swelling. Axons usually originate from the cell body and may exhibit spines on their axon hillock and initial segment. Axons; which can only be followed for 50-100 micrometers until they pass out of the section or abruptly cease to impregnate; often give off one or more thin; beaded collaterals that appear to be confined to the vicinity of the cell. No preferred axonal trajectory was observed. A few smaller spine sparse neurons were observed in the dorsal portion of the lateral subdivision and dorsomedial to this subdivision (Fig. 2; cell A). Axons of these neurons usually branch several times in the vicinity of the cell.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminals juxtacapsular subdivision
general_description: Between the lateral subdivision and the internal capsule is a small region that may be termed the â€˜*juxtacapsular subdivisionâ€ of the BST (Fig. 1). This subdivision consists of neurons with small; ovoid perikarya (9-13 micrometers in diameter) and several thin dendrites that give rise to numerous; wavy branches (Fig. 2; cell C). Dendritic branches; which have a dense covering of spines; are restricted to the confines of this small region (Fig. 2). Axons originate from the perikaryon or the proximal portion of a primary dendrite but can only be followed for a short distance before they leave the section or cease to impregnate. They usually emit one or more thin; beaded collaterals that appear to remain confined to the subdivision. Additional small; spiny neurons; very similar to those of the juxtacapsular subdivision; are seen adjacent to the compact; undivided portion of the stria terminalis located between the internal capsule and lateral ventricle (Fig. 3). Similar cells are also observed encapsulating the commissural bundle of the stria during its ventromedial descent towards the anterior commissure.

general_description: Group e; the most horizontally oriented subdivision; is a ventral large-celled subgroup which caudally replaces group c. Medilly it lies contiguous to the most rostral and lateral cells of the rostral paraventricular nucleus (RPa; Plate 8) and the two groups form a winglike shape spreading laterally from the ventricle and over the rostral surface of the fornix.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial subdivision
general_description: The medial subdivision of BST extends from the region of the anterior commissure (Fig 1) to the level of the preoptic hypothalamic junction (Fig. 6). Neurons are basically similar in all portions of the subdivision (Figs. 5;7;8). Most cells have ovoid perikarya that are 14-18 micrometers long and 10-13 micrometers wide. Two or three dendrites arise from the cell body and branch rather sparingly. Denddtes may extend 300-400 micrometers and vary in spine density. Axons originate from cell bodies primary dendrites; or the proximal portion of  secondary dendrites (compare cells B;C; and E of Fig. 7.) and do not appear to display a preferred orientation.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The gray matter surrounding the stria terminalis was rather loosely referred to as the interstitial nucleus of the stria by Cajal ('11); whereas Johnston ('23) applied the term bed of the stria terminalis somewhat more specifically to a  region extending from the temporal pole caudally; to the base of the olfactory peduncle (including part of the head of the caudate nucleus) rostrally. The temporal end of Johnston's bed has since come to be regarded as part of the amygdala; and only a few neurons lie along the body of the stria  terminalis itself; at least in the rat (Leonard and Scott; '71). Thus; medial parts of the rostra1 end of Johnston's bed are now commonly referred to as the bed nucleus of the stria  terminalis (BST). The anterior division can be further parcellated into dorsal; lateral; and ventral areas (Figs. 1-3). They form a continuouscellular mass that is traversed by the anterior commissure; which serves as a landmark separating the anterior dorsal from the anterior ventral area.
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis anterior division
general_description: The main bundles of the stria terminalis are primarily directed ventrally; thereby clearly dividing the BST into a posterior and an anterior division. This is especially marked in horizontal sections (see Fig. 33); where stria1 axons form what amounts to a gently curved septum between these two  divisions. Relatively large blood vessels frequently run dorsoventrally along the anterior border of this septum. Collator note: the abbreviation of this division was adapted by the collator.
reference: Ju G. & Swanson L.W. (I) Studies on the cellular architecture of the bed nuclein of the stria terminalis in the rat: I. Cytoarchitecture

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis anterolateral area
general_description: This area consists of a large undifferentiated region with three relatively distinct nuclei embedded within it. The cells in the undifferentiated region are generally small; and round to oval anteriorly; but many larger cells with varying shapes begin to appear caudally (especially ventrally). Rostrally; the anterolateral area borders the anterodorsal area; from which it can be distinguished by the more uniform appearance of its cells (Fig. 10). Caudally; the anterolateral area abuts the posterior division; while ventrally it merges without a clear boundary with the anteroventral area.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis ventral nucleus
general_description: This nucleus occupies the triangular area ventral to the magnocellular nucleus and narrows down as the caudal extension of the anterior division of the BST comes to lie ventral to the posterior division. It consists primarily of medium-sized multipolar neurons (Fig. 29); which contrasts sharply with the dorsally adjacent large cells of the magnocellular nucleus and the medially adjacent smaller neurons of the medial and anterior hypothalamic areas.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis rhomboid nucleus
general_description: A small nucleus that is more or less rhomboid in shape when viewed in frontal sections can be identified caudal and ventral to the oval and juxtacapsular nuclei; lying between the internal capsule and the ventromedially coursing commissural component ofthe stria terminalis of De Olmos ('72; and De Olmos and Ingram; '72). The uniform size of its round-to-multipolar neurons (Figs. 13; 14) distinguishes it from ventrally adjacent; undifferentiated parts of the anterolateral area. Although the borders of the rhomboid nucleus are not as clearly defined on cytoarchitectonic grounds as some of the other nuclei in the BST; it is well characterized by the presence of substance P (Ju et al.; '89)- and somatostatin (Woodhams et al.; '83)-immunoreactive neurons.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis anteroventral area
general_description: This is the most heterogeneous region of the BST and also the longest in the anteroposterior dimension. As shown in Figures 1-8; it is bordered dorsally by the anterior commissure; ventrally and medially by the substantia innominata and lateral and medial preoptic areas; and more caudally by the lateral and anterior hypothalamic areas. The neurons in this area are generally small; especially anteriorly; but tend to become larger at more caudal levels. There appear to be at least six distinct cell groups embedded within the anteroventral area.

general_description: This is a small but well-defined cell group that lies along the ventrolateral border of the anteroventral area. It consists mainly of small to medium-sized; oval-to-spindle-shaped neurons that are oriented tangential to the borders of the area (Figs. 21-23).It begins rostrally at about the same level as the parastrial nucleus (Fig. 2); and then shifts laterally; almost reaching the lateralmost edge of the BST (Fig. 19).

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis dorsomedial nucleus
general_description: This is a loosely arranged; relatively ill-defined nucleus that partly envelopes the lateral aspect of the parastrial nucleus. Anteriorly; it is distinguished from the undifferentiated part of the anteroventral area by the presence of scattered; medium sized multipolar cells and by the overall dorsomedial to ventrolateral orientation of the cells (Figs. 17; 24; 25). The dorsomedial nucleus is bordered caudally (and laterally) by the dorsolateral nucleus (Figs. 24; 26).

general_description: This nucleus appears at levels of the anteroventral area of the BST where the dorsomedial nucleus begins to disappear. It lies ventral to the anterior commissure; lateral to the dorsomedial nucleus; and dorsomedial to the magnocellular nucleus. Its cells are medium-sized; and many are multipolar or triangular in shape; with their long axes arranged dorsomedially to ventrolaterally (Figs. 24; 26).

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis magnocellular nucleus
general_description: Many darkly stained; large plump neurons stand out markedly within posterior parts of the anteroventral area. These cells are similar in appearance to; but differ immunohistochemically from (Ju et al.; '89); cells in the posterodorsal (preoptic) nucleus (Fig. 28). Rostrally; the magnocellular nucleus first occupies a region ventrolateral to the crossing of the anterior commissure (Fig. 27); lateral to the dorsolateral nucleus. Immediately caudal to this level it assumes the appearance of a horizontal band of cells adjacent to the posterodorsal (preoptic) nucleus medially; with no clear boundary between them (Figs. 19; 28). It then extends dorsolaterally to reach the ventral border of the anterolateral area; and even appears to invade as clusters of cells into the territory of thelatter. Strands of cells can also be seen to penetrate among fiber bundles of the stria terminalis; ascending to the lateral part of the posterior division.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis principal (encapsulated)  nucleus
general_description: The most prominent component of the posterior division is a large; sausage-shaped nucleus; which may correspond to the encapsulated nucleus referred to but not illustrated by Young (’36) in the rabbit (also see Simerly and Swanson; ’86). The region that we refer to specifically consists of densely packed; small; round to oval-shaped neurons (Figs. 30; 31). Rostrally; it lies just ventral to the tip of the lateral ventricle (Fig. 5); whereas at more caudal levels it spreads ventrally and medially; and its caudal tip comes to lie  just beneath the descending column of the fornix (Fig. 8). Caudal parts of the posterodorsal (preoptic) nucleus abut the ventral and caudal border of the principal nucleus; although cells in the latter tend to be distinctly smaller than those in the posterodorsal nucleus.

The cytoarchitecture of the dorsal nucleus is very similar to that of the principal nucleus; although the two  nuclei are completely separated by dense bundles of stria terminalis fibers (Fig. 5).

general_description: ...band or ridge of gray matter lying medial to the caudate nucleus and forming the bed of the stria terminalis and of the anterior commissure as well...This mass which forms the bed of the stria terminalis and anterior commissure may be readily recognized in the mammals and in lower orders of vertebrates. The rat possesses a prominent mass of gray lying over and behind the anterior commissure which might almost be called a special nucleus of the stria terminalis (fig. 19). It consists of a dense collection of cells near the point of contact of the stria medullaris and fornix columns; which is continuous with that mass of gray matter which passes down behind the anterior commissure and follows the fornix column toward the hypothalamus. A short distance behind this point; the gray matter accompanying the stria is reduced to a mere vestige as in other forms. Going forward from the anterior commissure the bed of the stria very clearly continues forward and downward over the medial surface of the anterior limb of the commissure to join the medial part of the head of the caudate and the nucleus accumbens.

brain_part: Anterior part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The anterior strial bed nucleus is a strip of gray matter extending from the nucleus accumbens to just behind the decussation of the anterior commissure. The striatum forms its lateral border throughout. The drawings in Figure 2 indicate its position and shape at various rostrocaudal levels (Pellegrino et al.; '79). Rostrally; the cells in the anterior strial bed nucleus encircle the interbulbar part of the anterior commissure. Farther caudally; the fibers of the temporal limb of the commissure cut across the strial bed nucleus; dividing it into dorsal and ventral halves. At the decussation of the commissure; the anterior strial bed nucleus has its largest cross-sectional area; only the lateral half extends to level A6.8. All bundles of the stria terminalis except the preoptic bundle course through the region of the strial bed nucleus at the anterior commissural decussation (Johnston; '23; Gurdjian; '25; Berkelbach Van der Sprenkel; '26; Smith; '30; Krieg; '32; Humphrey; '36; Young; '36; Fox; '40; Valverde; '63). Some fibers in the supracommissural bundle extend forward; coursing through rostral parts of the anterior strial bed nucleus (Johnston; '23; Smith; '30; Humphrey; '36; Young; '36; Fox; '40); this is the same bundle that de Olmos and Ingram ('73) called the parolfactory radiation.

brain_part: Posterior part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: ...the posterior strial bed nucleus extends in a dorsolateral to ventromedial direction occupying a wedge between the basal ganglia and the diencephalon. The posterior strial bed nucleus is most prominent at level A6.8; only the dorsolateral part extendsto level A6.4; and it disappears farther caudally (drawings; Fig. 11). Since it invades the posterolateral preoptic area; this part of the strial bed nucleus is often called the “preoptic continuation” (Gurdjian; ’27; Loo; ’31; Krieg; ’32; Young; ’36; Fox; ’40). The preoptic component of the stria terminalis (Johnston; ’23; Gurdjian; ’25; Berkelbach Van der Sprenkel; ’26; Smith; ’30; Krieg; ’32; Humphrey; ’36; Young; ’36; Fox; ’40); called the retrocommissural component by de Olmos and Ingram; (‘73); permeates the posterior strial bed nucleus. The orientation of the strial fibers may be responsible for the palisades of cells seen in ventrolateral parts (area D; Fig. 9).

general_description: There is no commonly accepted parcellation of the area that includes the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis and is traversed by the anterior commissure and the stria medullaris. Some authors have distinguished between the bed nuclei of the stria terminalis and the anterior commissure; the latter being said to lie either medial (Johnston; '23; Loo; '31; Young; '36; Ariens Kappers et al.; '36; Lauer; '45) or anterolateral (Bleier; '61; Berman and Jones; '79) to the former. In the rat; there seems to be no justification for distinguishing between the two; and the region as a whole will here be referred to as the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (following Fox; '40; Jeserich; '45; Johnson; '57; Andy and Stephan; '64). All parts of this complex appear to receive inputs from the amygdala by way of the stria terminalis (DeOlmos and Ingram; '72; Krettek and Price; '78). The bed nucleus consists of small to medium- sized neurons (7-20 micrometers in diameter).

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: Johnston('23) has described this for the rat. He draws attention tothe fact that it is found in the plane of the anterior commissureand becomes continuons with the head of the caudateand the nucleus accumbens rostrally; while caudally it followsthe fornix columns to the hypothalamus. He thinksthat this bed nucleus accompanies the stria all the waythrough its course from the amygdaloid complex. However;we want to stress this one point: that the stria terminalisin its course on the ventrolateral aspect of the fornix isaccompanied by very few nerve cells. Thus; we have notbeen able to see a nerve cell in as many as fifteen to twentysections in the serial order; in the preparations at hand. Itis also noted that a close relation exists between this and thebed nucleus of the anterior commissure.

general_description: The stria medullaris is accompanied in the reptiles and in mammalian embryon by a ridge of gray matter; the bed of the stria terminalis. In adult mammals; this is reduced along the main part of the course of the stria to the condition of a few scattered cells among the fibres of the tract. [This structure belongs] to the olfactory system; of which the bed of stria terminalis is a part.

The bed nucleus is a complex collection of cells which forms the neuronal matrix for the fibers of stria terminalis as they leave their site at the rostroventral tip of the lateral ventricle and descend through the hypothalamus. Rostrally the fibers and bed nucleus lie dorsal; then rostral; caudal; and ventral to the anterior commissure (Plates 3-5). Although the stria terminalis fibers disperse throughout the medial hypothalamus; its bed nucleus is obvious as a discrete cell collection only in the rostral part of the dorsal region. The entire collection of cells; ST; becomes divided by strial bundles into smaller groups. These have here been designated as subgroups a; b; c; d; and e; although it should be noted that this is considered to be an arbitrary cytoarchitectonic subdivision in the absence of data concerning differential connections.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The BST is positioned between the ACB rostrally and a transverse plane parallel to the anterior border of the prethalamic stria medullaris caudally (see S2). Medially the BST is bound by the lateral septum and the MP0A; laterally by the internal capsule and the GP (see H6). The nucleus is traversed by the fibers of the anterior commissure (ac) and the commissural component of the stria terminalis (sbc); the stria terminalis itself spreads out into the BST. Dorsally the BST extends to the ventral surface of the lateral ventricle (see T5; S3). Proceeding from rostral to caudal the BST overlies the SIC and the LPOA (T3-T4). Whereas the structures last mentioned extend in a caudolateral direction; the BST continues strictly caudally and arches downwards along the medial surfaces of the SIL and LPOA (T6). In this position the BST is interposed between the SIL and LPOA laterally and the MPOA; the POM and the AHA medially (H4-H5). The caudalmost extreme of the BST protrudes slightly into the AHA (T7; Sl). The outline of the BST corresponds rather well with that indicated by Swanson and Cowan ('79); Bleier et al. ('79); and de Olmos et al. ('85).
reference: Geeraedts L.M.G.; Nieuwenhuys R. & Veening J.G. Medial forebrain bundle of the rat: III Cytoarchitecture of the rostral (telencephalic) part of the medial forebrain bundle bed nucleus

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis subarea 1
general_description: BST1 and BST2 occupy the rostrodorsal portion of the BST and are located dorsal and rostral to the anterior commissure. They appear to constitute two vertically oriented cellular plates parallel to one another; the caudal plate isidentified here as BSTl (T4-T6; Sl-S3); the rostral as BST2 (see below). Both plates extend from rostromedial to caudolateral. This means that BST1 has a more medial and BST2 a more lateral position within the bed nucleus. BST1 adjoins the LSNV on its medial side. The cell-poor zona limitanswhich according to Swanson and Cowan ('79) separates the BST from the LSNV; is considered here as a part of BST1. Laterally BS1 adheres to the GP and the internal capsule (T5- T6). BST1 has a more heterogeneous cellular composition than BST2; it consists of small and small to medium-sized neurons; intermingled with occasional larger cell bodies. The BST1 and the caudally adjoining portion of the BST4 contain a moderate amount of cholecystokininimmunoreactive cell bodies. In male rats significantly more cholecystokinin-positive neurons can be observed in these two subareas of the BST than in female rats (Micevych et al.; '88).
reference: Geeraedts L.M.G.; Nieuwenhuys R. & Veening J.G. Medial forebrain bundle of the rat: III Cytoarchitecture of the rostral (telencephalic) part of the medial forebrain bundle bed nucleus

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis subarea 2
general_description: BST2 (T1-T5; S1-S3; H6) adjoins rostrally the striatal region. It borders on the LSN medially and on the GP and the internal capsule laterally. The cell bodies of BST2 resemble the small to medium-sized neurons of the CPU. Within BST2 they are evenly distributed and rather densely crowded. The so-called juxtacapsular subdivision of the BST as described by McDonald ('83) is considered here to be part of the BST2. Within the BST2 considerable numbers of neurotensin- (Jennes et al.; '82); GABA-T- (Nagai etal.; W); dynorphin B-; dynorphin A-; met-enkephalin- (Fallon and Leslie; '86); galanin-(Melander et al.; '86); and corticotrophin- releasing factor-like (Sakanaka et al.; '87) irnmunoreactive perikarya have been demonstrated...

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis subarea 3
general_description: BST3 forms the rostroventral portion of the BST and lies beneath the BST1; the BST2; and the anterior commissure (T3-T5; S1-S3; H4-H6). The BST3 overlies the SIC and LPOA. It is caudally flanked by the BST5. BST3 is characterized mainly by medium-sized and polymorphic neurons which tend to arrange themselves in several clusters. The medial wall of RST3 is just below the anterior commissure indented by a nucleus; previously described by Raisman and Field ('73) as the round nucleus of the preoptic region and recently designated by Simerly et al. ('84) as the parastrial nucleus of the medial preoptic area (POPS; T4; S1; H5). Ventral to the anterior commissure; i.e.; within the confines of the BST3; a dense cluster of atriopeptin-like reactive neurons have been identified by Standaert et al. ('86). The BST3 and also the BST1 are occupied by a considerable number of estrogen-concentrating neurons (Fahrbach et al.; '86). The BST2 and the lateral half of the BST3 appeared to be a significant source of peptidergic fibers coursing towards the parabrachial nucleus; the central gray and the dorsal vagal complex (Gray and Magnuson; '87).

brain_part: Intermediate medium-sized-celled column of the posterior part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The intermediate column (Figs. 15D; 16A; 27 A; and 27B) is composed of loosely arranged; more lightly stained; medium-sized; spindle- and angular-shaped cells. Throughout most of its course; this column lies just rostrally apposed to the stria medullaris (Figs. 28A; 28C; and 28E). At its caudal end; it separates from the dispersing fibers of the stria medullaris; but at the same time comes to lie rostral and ventral to the descending columns of the fornix. Caudally; the cells of the medium-sized-celled column merge imperceptibly with the medium-sized-celled portion of the anterior hypothalamus (Fig. 16A); whereas; dorsally and laterally; the cells of the medium-sized-celled column form the floor of the lateral ventricle.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis subarea 4
general_description: BST4 occupies the caudal one-third of the RST and lies behind BST1 and BST5 (T6-T7; Sl-S3; H4-H6). It is a vertically oriented mass of cells. Dorsally it is separated from the ventricular lining by a small molecular zone; ventrally it merges with the AHA. BST4 can be divided into a medial and a lateral cellular column (not indicated in the tracings). The medial column consists of small to medium-sized; rather darkly staining and densely packed neurons. In the ventral part of this column the neurons are arranged in verticalarrays. The column is separated from the stria medullaris and the fornix by a small; cell-sparse zone containing some BST4-like neurons and; moreover; a few medium to large-sized; darkly staining neurons. Dorsomedially the BAC protrudes into BST4. The lateral column of BST4 is less densely crowded with cell bodies than the medial column and contains preponderantly medium-sized neurons intermingled with some larger neurons. The medium-sized to large neurons positioned lateral to the lateral column; which have been included by de Olrnos et al. ('85) in their posterior group of the medial division of the BST; were identified in this report as a part of BST5 (T6). The ventrocaudal portion of the BST4 corresponds with the so-called preoptic continuation of the BST as previously described by Gurdjian ('27) and McDonald ('83).
reference: Geeraedts L.M.G.; Nieuwenhuys R. & Veening J.G. Medial forebrain bundle of the rat: III Cytoarchitecture of the rostral (telencephalic) part of the medial forebrain bundle bed nucleus

brain_part: Anterior part of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The anterior part is located dorsal to the crossing fibers of the anterior commissure; lying within the course of the dorsal component of the stria terminal is as it traverses the dorsal and rostral aspects of the commissure (Fig. 15B). It borders the ventral lateral septum rostromedially and reaches the rostrodorsal border of the ventral part of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (BSTMV) ventro­caudally. Dorsally; the stria terminalis separates the anterior part of the medial bed nucleus from the posterior part of the medial; whereas ventrally the anterior and posterior parts of the medial bed nucleus are separated by the commissural component of the stria terminalis. Medially; the cells of the anterior part of the medial bed nucleus are medium sized and irregular in shape and are dispersed among the fibers of the stria terminalis. More laterally; the cells are smaller and more tightly packed.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis subarea 5
general_description: BST5 is a transversally oriented; curved cellular plate of only a few cells' thickness (T6; SI-S3; H4-H6). It reaches dorsally up to the commissural component of the stria terminalis (stc); which passes through the BST5 on its way to the anterior commissure. The cell bodies located within the BST5-trajectory of the stc are indicated by de Olmos et al. ('85) as the bed nucleus of the stc. BST5 extends downwards between BSTl and BST3 rostrally and BST4 caudally. The medium-sized to large and rather darkly staining cell bodies of BST5 are very conspicuous; which makes it easy to demarcate BST5 from the neighbouring parts of the BST (Fig. 22). The number of cell bodies within BST5 increases from dorsal to ventral. These neurons are unevenly distributed; giving the impression of the presence of several cellular subgroups within BST5. One of these subgroups is a small cluster of large; darkly staining and densely packed cell bodies; located at the medial margin of BST5. This cluster was identified by Simerly et al. ('84) as the posterodorsal preoptic nucleus (POPD; H5); it probably corresponds with the anterior commissure nucleus as depicted in the atlas of Paxinos and Watson ('86). Van Leeuwen and Caffe ('83) found numerous vasopressine immunoreactive neuronswithin the BST and the anterior commissural nucleus; these two loci are likely to correspond with our BST5 and POPD; respectively. In the present study the neurons which closely surround the anterior commissure are not considered to constitute a separate nucleus commissurae anterioris (Koeinig and Klippel; '63); but are rather taken to belong either to the BST; or the septa1 region or the medial preoptic area.

general_description: BST6 is rather densely crowded with preponderantly small and some medium-sized oval-shaped and rather pale staining neurons (Fig. 23; S2-S3).

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: At the rostral end of the extended amygdala; the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis forms part of the floor of the lateral ventricle and is bounded dorsomedially by the ventral aspect of the lateral septal nucleus and laterally by the internal capsule; which separates it from the caudate putamen and globus pallidus (Figs. 15B-15D). Caudally; it is successively bounded by the stria terminalis; the stria medullaris; and in part the columns of the fornix. Rostrally; it merges with the caudomedial portions of the nucleus accumbens; whereas; ventromedially; it merges with the preoptic area. Ventrolaterally and caudolaterally; it merges with the sublenticular territories that stretch out laterally immediately below the globus pallidus (Figs. 15D-15F). Generally; the rostral border of the bed nucleus may be viewed as indistinct with the nucleus accumbens. It sometimes has been convenient to identify this border by the use of histochemistry for acetylcholinesterase; because acetylcholinesterase stains densely within the accumbens and generally more sparsely within the bed nucleus. However; almost every other histochemical stain or receptor that densely marks the bed nucleus also densely labels portions of the caudomedial accumbens (e.g.; Fig. 9A); and to some extent neurons that project to areas typical of the extended amygdala are found in these zones (e.g.; Fig. 13) (Nauta et at.; 1978; Grove; 1988a; 1988b).
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Ventral part of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The ventral part of the medial bed nucleus is located ventral to the anterior commissure and is composed of medium-sized cells interposed between the parastrial nucleus [i.e.; the round nucleus of Raisman and Fields (1973)] and the ventral part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (Fig. 15B'). Rostrodorsally; it reaches the anterior part of the medial bed nucleus; whereas it borders. the intermediate part of the lateral bed nucleus caudally. The cells are loosely arranged; contrasting with those of the adjacent parastrial nucleus; and are larger and more chromophilic than the more closely spaced neu­rons of the ventral lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis. Ventrally; a cell-poor zone separates it from the preoptic area.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Posterior part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The posterior part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis. is a heterogeneous group of cells ar­ranged in columnar fashion; following the postcommissural fibers of the stria terminal is (Figs. 15C; 15D; 16A; 16B; 27 A; and 27B). It is the largest and longest of the major divisions of the bed nucleus; extending continuously from the uppermost caudal part of the paraseptal bed nucleus; behind the anterior commissure; to the hypothalamus; where it merges with the anterior hypothalamic area. For most of its dorsoventral extent; it borders the stria medul­laris caudally; and borders the fornix medially. Rostrally; at the paraseptal level; it is apposed to the intermediate part of the lateral bed nucleus. Based on its cytoarchitecture; the posterior part of the medial bed nucleus can be subdi­vided into three cell columns: a medial small- or dense­celled column (BSTMPm); an intermediate medium-sized­celled column (BSTMPi); and a lateral large-celled column (BSTMPl).
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: It [ventral part of the lateral septal nucleus] is separated ventrolaterally from the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis by a cell-free zona limitans (Johnston; '13). This subdivision is said to be particularly distinct in the cat; where Andy and Stephan ('64) refer to it alone as the lateral septal nucleus.

brain_part: Posterior part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The posterior part of the lateral bed nucleus (BSTLP) accounts for the majority of the cells in this complex (Figs. 15B; 15C; and 28). It surrounds the ventral and caudal aspects of the dorsal part; with its main mass found posterior to the dorsal part of the lateral bed nucleus; where it replaces the dorsal part; but also extends ventrally and laterally; where it merges with the anterodorsal or central division of the sublenticular extended amygdala. In Nissl-stained sections; the cell composition of the posterior lateral bed nucleus resembles that of the dorsal lateral bed nucleus; except that it is somewhat more heterogeneous; containing smaller elongated cells that are more closely spaced.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Medial dense-celled column of the posterior part of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: This column is composed of homogeneous; densely packed; darkly stained; round to oval neurons; located in the extreme medial aspect of the posterior part of the medial bed nucleus (Figs. 15D; l6A; 27 A; and 27B). The small-celled column extends ventromedially and stops at a level adjacent to the posterodorsal preoptic nucleus. In the ventral part of the small-celled column; the densely packed cells form an oval cylinder in horizontal sections (Fig. 28A); whereas dorsally this column is larger and more round. The cells in the dorsal subventricular portion of this column expand to form a wider head; which appears to be partially encapsulated by a cell-poor zone of fibers. These cells are more loosely packed and even more homogeneous in appearance than those in the deeper portions of this column; where larger cells are sometimes intermixed with the predominantly small-cell population. The cells in the dorsal part of the small-celled column lie adjacent to the accessory olfactory tract as it separates from the stria terminalis.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

general_description: Area 25 lies dorsal to the tenia tecta and has three cellular layers: a dense external layer II-III whose border with layer I is irregular; an inner layer V which has slightly larger pyramidal cells than those in layer II-III; and a layer VI of somewhat smaller neurons. In Figure 3 the arrow delineates layer II-III from layer V in area 25 [...].

brain_part: Lateral column of the posterior part of the medial bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The lateral column contains a more heterogeneous population of neurons than the other two divisions of the posterior medial bed nucleus. Most of the cells in the large­celled column are loosely arranged in rows oriented parallel to the incoming fibers of the stria terminalis. These cells range from medium size to large; with some of the largest cells of the posterior medial bed nucleus occurring in this column. Collator note: the abbreviation is not provided in text; but is used in Figures.
