brain_part: Juxtacapsular part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The juxtacapsular part of the lateral bed nucleus is a small lens-shaped cell aggregate made up of small ovoid cells that fill a shallow concavity made by the medial surface of the internal capsule at the same plane as the crossing fibers of the anterior commissure. Its medial edge borders the dorsal and posterior lateral bed nucleus; but is distinguishable from these areas by its smaller and more densely packed cells.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Intraamygdaloid bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The intraamygdaloid bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (Figs. 151; 15J; 18A; 18B; 20A; and 20B) is a relatively cell­poor area located lateral to the dorsal part of the medial nucleus and is traversed by fibers destined for the stria terminalis. The interamygdaloid bed nucleus cells are medium sized; but are larger and stain more lightly than those of the medial amygdala. In cholinesterase-stained sections (Figs. 18A and 20A); the intraamygdaloid bed nucleus of the stria terminalis has a light to moderate reaction compared with that of the surrounding neuropil; except for that of the basolateral nucleus; which is much stronger. In Timm's stained sections the intraamygdaloid bed nucleus (Figs. 18B and 20B) appears as an area with very dense silver precipitate; but which is lighter than the very dense stain in the adjacent medial amygdala and the very dense precipitate in the main intercalated cell mass; whose sagittal limb invades the intraamygdaloid bed nucleus.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis supracapsular par
general_description: The supracapsular part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis is a term that-for the rat-encompasses interrupted cell columns accompanying the stria terminalis as it traverses the dorsal part of the internal capsule. As with the sublenticular extended amygdala; the supracapsular bed nucleus includes elements of both the medial and the central divisions of the extended amygdala. Incidental observations; made in the course of other retrograde labeling experiments; indicate that there is also a medial to lateral segregation of the cells associated with the medial and central divisions of the extended amygdala; respectively.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis lateral division
general_description: The lateral division of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis is in the general form of an irregular truncated pyramid; with its base apposed to the medial side of the internal capsule; which forms its medial boundary (Figs. 15B and 15C). Rostrally; it adjoins the posterior aspect of the nucleus accumbens ventrally and the caudate putamen dorsally. The medial boundary of the later.al bed nucleus is marked by the compact fibers of the stria terminalis. It rests atop the anterior commissure and extends slightly rostral along its anterior limb. Caudally; it dips ventrally to surround the posterior limb of the anterior commissure. Moving from rostrodorsal to caudoventral; the lateral bed nucleus tapers somewhat until it fuses with the rostromedial end of the sublenticular extended amygdala.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.
referenceforfacet: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Dorsal part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The dorsal part of the lateral bed nucleus is composed of pale-staining rounded cells and is relatively homogeneous in appearance. It has a teardrop shape; whose long axis is oriented along the course of the stria terminalis dorsocaudally to rostroventrally; and because of this it resembles a double convex lens in frontal and horizontal section (Figs. 15B and 31B). On histochemical grounds this may be further subdivided into (i) capsular (BSTLDC) and (ii) central (BSTLDcn) parts; with the capsular portion demonstrating a richer substance P terminal field; but much poorer tyrosine hydroxylase terminals (Fig. 31B).
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Dorsal part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis capsular portion

brain_part: Ventral part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The ventral part of the lateral bed nucleus; as its name implies; occupies the ventrolateral quadrant of the lateral bed nucleus; starting just below the anterior commissure (Fig. 15B') and extending caudally until it merges with the posterior part of the lateral bed nucleus. It is continuous on its 'lateral' edge with extended amygdaloid neurons; which envelop the posterior limb of the anterior commissure in the territory we have termed the interstitial nucleus of the posterior limb of the anterior commissure. The ventral part of the lateral bed nucleus is composed of a mixed population of neurons; including many that are larger; more angular; and more darkly stained than those in the dorsal part.

brain_part: Intermediate part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The intermediate part of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis is composed of predominantly angular dark-staining large (15-20 micrometers) neurons (the largest of all neurons in the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis); which are interposed berween the remaining divisions of the lateral bed nucleus of the stria terminalis and the posterior medial bed nucleus. The cells form a narrow wedge in sagittal sections; but appear similar to a flattened crescent in horizontal sections (Figs. 28a; 28E; and 32). The long axes of these cells are oriented in an oblique angle; which is parallel to fibers traversing the intermediate bed nucleus in a lateroventral to mediodorsal direction. The intermediate bed nucleus of the stria terminalis extends dorsally until it reaches the dark-staining cell groups that accompany the commissural component of the stria terminalis (that is; the bed nucleus of the commissural component of the stria terminalis). Ventrally; the intermediate bed nucleus merges with the lateral preoptic area; whereas; laterally; it merges with the sublenticular extended amygdala.
reference: Alheid G.F; de Olmos J.S. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis intermediate division
general_description: The intermediate division of the BST is composed of predominantly angular dark staining (15 microemeters to 20 micrometers) neurons (the largest of all neurons in the BST) which are interposed between the BSTL and posterior BSTM. The cells form a narrow wedge when seen in saggital section; but appear to a flattened crescent in horizontal sections. The ling axes of these cells are oriented in an oblique angle which is parallel to fibers traversing the BSTI in lateroventral to mediodorsal direction. The BSTI extends dorsally until it reaches the dark staining cell groups which accompany the commissural component of the stria terminalis (that is; the bed nucleus of the commissural component of the stria terminalis). Ventrally; the BSTI merges with the lateral preoptic area while laterally it merges with the SLSI.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial division posterior part
general_description: The posterior BSTM is a heterogeneous group of cells arranged in columnar fashion following the postcommissural fibers of the stria terminalis. It is the largest and longest of all divisions of the BST extending continuously from the caudal uppermost part of the paraseptal BST; behind the anterior commissure to the anterior hypothalamus where it merges with the anterior hypothalamic area (AH). For most of its dorsoventral extent; it caudally borders the stria medullaris; and medially borders the fornix; becoming separated at the paraseptal level from the lateral and ventral divisions of the BST by the intermediate division of the BST and the dorsal extension of the preoptic area.
reference: de Olmos J.; Alheid G.F. & Beltramino C.A.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial division posterior part small celled column
general_description: Based on cytoarchitecture; the posterior BSTM can be subidivided into three cell columns: an anteriomedial small celled column; a medial medium celled column; and lateral large celled column. BSTMPsc is composed of homogeneous densely packed darkly stained round to oval neurons; located in the extreme medial aspect of the posterior part of the BSTM. It extends ventromedially and stops at a level adjacent to the paraventricular commissural nucleus (Atlas; Fig. 16).

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis medial division posterior part medium celled column
general_description: Based on cytoarchitecture; the posterior BSTM can be subidivided into three cell columns: an anteriomedial small celled column; a medial medium celled column; and lateral large celled column. The medium celled column is composed by loosely arranged more lightly stained medium sized spindle and angular shaped cells. Throughout most of its course; this column lies just rostral and adjoining stria medullaris....

brain_part: Special nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The rat possesses a prominent mass of gray lying over and behind the anterior commissure which might almost be called a special nucleus of the stria terminalis (fig. 19). It consists of a dense collection of cells near the point of contact of the stria medullaris and fornix columns; which is continuous with that mass of gray matter which passes down behind the anterior commissure and follows the fornix column toward the hypothalamus.

general_description: The DL subnucleus is surrounded medially and ventrally by the anterior lateral (AL) subnucleus (Fig. 1B;C). Rostrally; AL spans between DL and VL; so a small portion of AL extends beneath the anterior commissure. Neurons in AL are medium-staining and oval- to teardrop-shaped with an indistinct nuclear border and little cytoplasm; they are often oriented parallel to the strial fibers which surround DL (Fig. 4C). Some scattered round; light-staining neurons from DL are also found in AL.

brain_part: Bed nucleus of the stria terminalis
general_description: The bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (or nucleus interstitialis striae terminalis) is a forebrain nucleus situated just ventral to the septal complex in close approximation with the anterior commissure. Originally described as ribbon of gray matter following the course of the stria terminalis (Johnston; '23); it consists of a somewhat heterogeneous collection of cell groups unified in constituting one of the major terminal fields of the amygdala by way of the stria terminalis (De Olmos and Ingram; '72; Krettek and Price; '78). Collator note: the initial nomenclature is adapted from Nomina Anatomica. Koenig & Klippel do not provide a text definition; nor references for stb.

general_description: KF is a homogeneous collection of cells having a mean average diameter of 16.5 &plusmn 0.3 micrometers (S.E.M.) (see Fig. 5). These cells are further characterized by their pyramidal shape; very distinct nucleolus; and the dark; fibrillar pattern of their cytoplasmic staining (Fig. 4F). A few cells belonging to KF can be seen in the most rostral part of PB; but the largest part of the nucleus is in the midportion of PB. By the level at which the SCP come into contact with the cerebellum; KF has disappeared. Rostrally KF is situated immediately ventral to the lateral pole of the SCP and medial to the lateral lemniscus (see Fig. 1B). Caudally; the external media1 nucleus (see below) is interposed between KF and the SCP (see Fig. 2A). Along its ventrolateral border KF is separated from the middle cerebellar peduncle by the principal sensory trigeminal nucleus. Throughout its extent; KF is bounded medially by the larger and more sparsely distributed neurons of the pontine tegmentum

general_description: The anterior cingulate area (figs. 3A;B; 4A;B) was described by Brodmann (’09); and designated area 24. It encompasses the “area infraradiata dorsalis (IRc)” and the supracallosal parts of the areas “infraradiata intermedia and ventralis (IRbbeta) andIRabeta” described by M. Rose (’27) and may correspond to a dorsal and supracallosal part of the anterior limbic cortex delimited by Rose and Woolsey (’48a). The anterior cingulate area is distinguished from the prelimbic area chiefly by its layer V which; especially rostrally; is conspicuously broader and less densely packed.

general_description: PBm is composed of a population of neurons which are heterogeneous with respect to size and morphology (see Fig. 5). Average cell diameters range from 8 to 19 micrometers. Morphologically; 3 cell types can be defined (Fig. 4B). A population of small lightly-staining round cells; about 12 micrometers mean average diameter; are found primarily in the caudal two-thirds of the nucleus. These are readily distinguished from a smaller population of a larger; more darkly-staining fusiform or multipolar cells; about 17 micrometers in mean average diameter; which tend to lie in a horizontal orientation. These neurons are also found in the caudal two-thirds of the nucleus; but are concentrated along the ventrolateral border of PBm. Finally; a medium-sized population of polygonal neurons; about 14 micrometers in mean average diameter; is found scattered throughout the rostral two-thirds of PBm. These cells are further distinguished by possessing a more prominent nucleolus than the other neurons of PBm.
reference: Fulwiler C.D. & Saper C.B. Subnuclear organization of the efferent connections of the parabrachial nucleus in the rat

general_description: This collection of large multipolar neurons; whose long axis is oriented horizontally; form a narrow strip which trails off from the lateral edge of PBm to interpose itself between KF and the SCP (see Figs. 2A; B; 4D). These cells extend laterally to the edge of the pons and abut directly on the dorsal border of the principal sensory trigeminal nucleus. They are distinguished from neurons of the latter nucleus which are much larger and have a distinctively coarse; granular cytoplasmic staining.

general_description: The infralimbic area (figs. 3B; 4A) of this account appears to be equivalent to the area so-named by Rose and Woolsey (’48a1; and corresponds to area 25 of Brodmann (’09); and; at least in part; to the “area infraradiata ventralis anterior (IRaalpha)” of M.Rose (’27). The chief characteristics of the infralimbic area are its relatively indistinct lamination and the relative unevenness of the outer border of layer 11; such that cells extend for varying distances into layer I.

general_description: Along the lateral aspect of PBl in the rostral third of PB; a very small cell group made up of neurons 12.5 &plusmn 0.2 micrometers in mean average diameter; indents the medial border of the lateral lemniscus. This is the extreme lateral nucleus (see Fig. 1A). The neuronal perikarya in this group are multipolar; slightly larger than the neighboring central lateral cells; and are characterized by darker cytoplasmic staining and greater packing density. These neurons are easily distinguished from the nearby cells of the dorsal nucleus of the lateral lemniscus which are much larger and have quite prominent nucleoli. The extreme lateral group is only about 2OO micrometers in its rostrocaudal extent. It begins rostrally as a round cluster lateral to the lateral tip of the SCP; gradually becoming vertically elongated as its cells shift medially to abut on the external lateral nucleus.

general_description: This relatively homogeneous group of medium sized cells; with a mean average diameter of 14.5 &plusmn 0.3 micrometers (see Fig. 5); is striking for its triangular contour and the fact that it extends dorsally above the rest of the nucleus. The perikarya of superior lateral neurons are pyramidal or multipolar; with a prominent large; round nucleus and nucleolus and dark; finally granular staining cytoplasm. Rostrally; these cells first appear scattered amid the fibers sweeping dorsolaterally from the SCP to form the ventral spinocerebellar tract. At this level; the cells are immediately dorsal to the SCP; but caudally they occupy a progressively more dorsal position as if swept upward by the fibers of the ventral spinocerebellar tract. The group takes on its characteristic triangular contour at the level at which the cerebral aqueduct begins to enlarge (see Fig. 1A). The superior lateral nucleus ends caudally at the level at which the ventral spinocerebellar tract shifts ventrolaterally to interpose itself between PBand the lateral lemniscus; just rostral to the point at which the inferior colliculus separates from the pons. The entire rostrocaudal extent of the superior lateral nucleus is only about 400 micrometers and it is confined entirely to the rostral third of PB.

general_description: This round ciuster of cells.; the internai lateral nucleus (see Figs. 1B; 3B; 4A); is set off by a relatively cell-poor zone which surrounds it. It is composed of a homogeneous group of neurons; 16.3 &plusmn 0.2 micrometers in mean average diameter (see Fig. 5). The perikarya are round; with indistinct nucleoli; and dark; coarsely granular cytoplasmic staining. The interna1 lateral group is situated immediately ventral to the dorsal surface of the pons; and dorsal to the medial tip of the SCP in the middle third of PB. Its rostral border is at the level at which the inferior colliculus separates from the pons; and it extends caudally only about 3OO micrometers; to the level at which the root of the trochlear nerve leaves the dorsal pons. It is situated amid the smaller and moresparsely distributed neurons of the central lateral nucleus.

general_description: The prelimbic area (figs. 3A;B) lies rostral and dorsal to the infralimbic area and extends forward to the tip of the frontal pole. This area was named by Brodmann (’09); and designated area 32. It appears to correspond largely to the pregenual portion of the “area infraradiata intermedia anterior (IRbalpha)” described by M. Rose (’27); and to a ventral; pregenuall part of the anterior limbic cortex delimited by Rose and Woolsey (’48a). The prelimbic area possesses a well-defined lamination and is characterized chiefly by its relatively homogeneous layer V; which contains large; darkly-staining cells; and by a tightly-packed bilaminar layer V1.

general_description: Although Brodmann's ('09) area 24 is consistently described in cytoarchitectural studies of the medial surface of the mouse (Rose; '12; Caviness; '751; rat (Kreig; '46a;b; Krettek and Price; '771; and monkey (Walker; '401; Walker recognized very early that this area is composed of a number of cytoarchitectural zones; of which the simplest adjoin the corpus callosum and the more complex occur at the lip of the cingulate sulcus. Smith ('45) made a similar observation; but further parcellation of area 24 was not made until just recently when it was shown that two subareas can be distinguished in area 24.

general_description: The central lateral nucleus is the largest subnucleus of PBl. It is composed of a relatively sparse population of neurons which occupy the majority of the area dorsal to the SCP in the rostral two-thirds of PB (see Fig. 1A;B). The perikarya have a mean average diameter of 12.2 &plusmn 0.2 micrometers (see Fig. 5); and are ovoid to fusiform in shape; with an indistinct nucleolus and cytoplasm which stains with a finely granular pattern; but less darkly than cells in the other subnuclei in PBl. The centrai lateral nucleus extends farther rostrally than any other in PB. At the rostral level at which many fibers of the SCP turn medially to decussate; central lateral cells can be seen mediodorsally; ventrolateral to the centra1 gray matter. More caudally; where the SCP is found more laterally; the central lateral cell group also extends laterally to span the medial-lateral extent of PBI. The caudal limit of the central lateral subnucleus is the point at which the lateral enlargement of the SCP comes into contact with the dorsal edge of the pons. In the caudal portions of the nucleus; the morphology of its cells becomes increasingly fusiform and the packing density greater; as if the SCP were compressing them against the dorsal surface of the pons as it approaches the cerebellum.

general_description: The ventral lateral nucleus consists of a band of cells along the dorsal surface of the SCP in the trough between its media; and lateral enlargements (see Figs. 1B; 2A;B; 3B). Rostrally; the cells aggregate along the dorsal surface of the SCP about 200 micrometers caudal to the rostral extreme of PB. They maintain this position throughout the extent of PB; up to about 300 micrometers rostral to the caudal extreme of PB; at which point the first large neurons of the superior vestibular nucleus appear.

general_description: The dorsal lateral nucleus is much shorter in rostral-caudal dimension; first appearing just rostral to the separation of the inferior colliculus from the pons and extending caudally only about 400 micrometers to the level at which the root of the fourth cranial nerve leaves the pons (see Figs. 1B; 2A). Its cells stain more darkly and have less distinct nuclei than central lateral neurons (Fig. 4C). Its dorsal border is the ventral spinocerebellar tract. Ventrally; it is bounded by the central lateral subnucleus and medially it borders upon the internal lateral cell group.

general_description: The neurons of the external Latera1 nucleus are cytologically similar to the cells in the extreme lateral subdivision but the borders of the two groups are easily defined. The external lateral subnucleus is further distinguished by a characteristic slightly metachromatic staining of the neuropil within it; which is unique among the subnuclei of PB. The external lateral cell group extends caudally almost to the point at which the lateral expansion of the SCP contacts the dorsal surface of the pons. Throughout its extent the external lateral subnucleus surrounds the dorsolateral edge of the SCP; abutting on neurons of PBm which surround the ventrolateral edge of the SCP (see Figs. 1;2).

general_description: Collator note: this brain nucleus is not defined explicitly in Fulwiler & Saper; 1984. However; is described as a heterogeneous collection of neuron types; in contradistinction with the external medial nucleus. Therefore; its explicit definition is the same as the medial division of PB; with the note that PBm also includes the homogeneous collection of neurons of the PBexm. The name and abbreviation we used are borrowed from the Swanson-98 rat nomenclature.

general_description: Area 32 (Figs. 1; 2; and 3) lies dorsal to area 25; abuts area 24a posteriorally; and has a distinguishable layer II. As in area 25; the neurons in all layers of area 32 are still very densely packed. Layer III of area 32 has cells which are smallerthan those in layer V; and the somewhat horizontally elongated neurons in layer VI are sometimes packed into thin sublayers.

general_description: [...] area 24a (Figs. 2 and 3); which is equivalent to Krettek and Price's ('77) ventral division of the anterior cingulate area; has neurons which are very evenly distributed throughout its entire depth. Area 32 shares this even distribution of neurons; but in area 32 the neurons; particularly those in layer V; are much larger and rounder than in area 24a. A thin layer of large cells comprising layer V is present in area 24a; although it is difficult to distinguish these neurons at low magnifications (Fig. 2); and the same is true of layer II. However; the cell size differences that mark these layers are quite apparent at higher magnification (Fig. 3).

general_description: In contrast to area 24a; area 24b; which is equivalent to Krettek and Price's ('77) dorsal division of the anterior cingulate area; has a sparse layer III; so that layer II is clearly visible and there is a broader layer V whose cells are larger than those of area 24a (Fig. 2). Layer VI has neurons that are somewhat smaller than those found in the same layer in area 32.
